In Japan, mathematicians put counting rods on a counting board, a sheet of cloth with grids, and used only vertical forms relying on the grids. An 18th-century Japanese mathematics book has a checker counting board diagram, with the order of magnitude symbols "åƒç™¾åä¸€åˆ†å˜æ¯›â€œ (thousand, hundred, ten, unit, tenth, hundredth, thousandth).
